Image Description:	Glass negative, full plate, 'Snowy River at Jindabyne', Kerry and Co, Sydney, Australia,  c. 1884-1917..
.
Silver gelatin dry plate glass negative in landscape format.  The image depicts the Snowy River near Jindabyne in the Snowy Mountain region of New South Wales.  The Snowy river is depicted in the centre of the image extending to the background of the image.  The river is surrounded by flat plains on the right side of the image and undulating hills on the left side of the image.  A road is partially depicted in the foreground in the lower right corner of the image.  The background of the image depicts the mountainous terrain of the Snowy Mountains.   The caption, studio mark and studio number are inscribed on the reverse of the negative..
.
Charles Kerry travelled extensively throughout the Snowy Mountains and was an active figure in the history of Australian skiing.  He promoted snow sports and organised winter parties to Kiandra.  With others, Kerry pressured for a road from Kiandra to the summit of Kosciuszko and the building of Hotel Kosciuszko.  Kerry led the first expedition to reach the summit of Kosciuszko under winter conditions in 1897.  With his photographic parties, Kerry captured many images of the Snowy Mountains landscape, such as this image of the Snowy River near Jindabyne..
.
